It can be said that this is the first time in Estonia's post-independence history that we are leading and creating an international initiative, taking on the responsibility of the presidency. We have been able to take practical steps this year - we have launched the Three Seas Fund in full, and as a result of our persuasive efforts, we have gained a number of member states. We have also established a technical secretariat for the Three Seas Initiative and have created a progress report for priority projects, involving the executive level. I believe that next week's summit will be a very strong step forward in this international project and there is nothing to be ashamed of here - it is thanks to Estonia's leadership that this has happened.
What is good is that today a list of officials who are being put on the European Union's sanctions list for their alleged involvement in the poisoning of Alexei Navalny will be made public.
